<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="section5-1-summary">
  <title>Section 5.1 Summary</title>

  <p>This section extended Chapter 3 ideas from two-group categorical comparisons to situations with more than two groups and/or more than two response categories.</p>

  <paragraphs>
    <title>What to Remember</title>
    <p><alert>One unified procedure:</alert> The same chi-squared framework handles homogeneity and association questions with the same computational structure.</p>
    <p><alert>Design drives interpretation:</alert> Randomized experiments support causal conclusions (for the studied participants), while observational studies support association statements but not causation.</p>
    <p><alert>Beyond p-values:</alert> Cell contributions/residuals explain where the evidence is coming from and help tell the practical story.</p>
    <p><alert>Connections to prior methods:</alert> For a <m>2\times 2</m> table, chi-squared results align closely with two-proportion <m>z</m>-tests (with <m>z^2 \approx \chi^2</m> for two-sided tests).</p>
  </paragraphs>

  <assemblage xml:id="section5-1-next-steps">
    <title>Looking Ahead</title>
    <p>In the next section, you will use an analogous strategy for comparing several population means. The key idea will again be to compare variability explained by groups to natural variability within groups, this time with the ANOVA <m>F</m>-statistic.</p>
  </assemblage>
</section>
